{{Other people|Edward Miller}} '''Edward S. Miller''' was the Deputy Assistant Director of the Inspections Division under [[Mark Felt]] with the [[United States]] [[Federal Bureau of Investigation]].
In November 1980, Miller, then head of the FBI's Domestic Intelligence Division, and Mark Felt were convicted after a seven-week federal jury trial of having "conspired to injure and oppress the citizens of the United States" and Miller was fined $3,500. While the convictions were being appealed in April 1981, President [[Ronald Reagan]] [[pardon]]ed both men. At the time of trial, Felt and Miller were the highest-ranking bureau employees to have been tried for a [[criminal offense]].<ref name="nytpardon">Pear, Robert (April 16, 1981). President Reagan Pardons 2 Ex-F.B.I. Officials in 1970's Break-Ins. ''[[The New York Times]]''</ref>
