==Criticism==
{{Main|Criticism of the War on Terror}}

[[File:World Can't Wait J4 Demo.jpg|thumb|Participants in a rally, dressed as hooded detainees]]

Criticism of the War on Terror addressed the issues, morality, efficiency, economics, and other questions surrounding the War on Terror and made against the phrase itself, calling it a [[misnomer]]. The notion of a "war" against "terrorism" has proven highly contentious, with critics charging that it has been exploited by participating governments to pursue long-standing policy/military objectives,<ref name="Monbiot2003">[[George Monbiot]], [http://www.monbiot.com/archives/2003/03/11/a-wilful-blindness "A Wilful Blindness"] ("Those who support the coming war with Iraq refuse to see that it has anything to do with US global domination"), ''monbiot.com'' (author's website archives), reposted from ''[[The Guardian]]'', 11 March 2003. Retrieved 28 May 2007.</ref> reduce [[civil liberties]],<ref name="Wired-FBI">{{cite news|url=https://www.wired.com/threatlevel/2008/03/fbi-tried-to-co/|title=FBI Tried to Cover Patriot Act Abuses With Flawed, Retroactive Subpoenas, Audit Finds|last=Singel|first=Ryan|date=13 March 2008|work=Wired |accessdate=13 February 2012}}</ref> and infringe upon human rights. It is argued that the term war is not appropriate in this context (as in [[War on Drugs]]) since there is no identifiable enemy and that it is unlikely international terrorism can be brought to an end by military means.<ref name="Richissin">{{cite news|url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/nationworld/2002023596_russanal02.html |title="War on terror" difficult to define |last=Richissin |first=Todd |date=2 September 2004 |work=The Baltimore Sun |accessdate=28 January 2009 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090114085106/http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/nationworld/2002023596_russanal02.html |archivedate=14 January 2009 }}</ref>

Other critics, such as [[Francis Fukuyama]], note that "[[Definition of terrorism|terrorism]]" is not an enemy, but a tactic; calling it a "war on terror", obscures differences between conflicts such as anti-occupation [[Insurgency|insurgents]] and international [[mujahideen]]. With a military presence in [[Iraq]] and [[Afghanistan]] and its associated collateral damage, [[Shirley Williams]] maintains this increases resentment and terrorist threats against the West.<ref>Williams, Shirley. "<cite>[https://www.theguardian.com/comment/story/0,3604,1072390,00.html The seeds of Iraq's future terror]</cite>". [[The Guardian]], 28 October 2003.</ref> There is also perceived U.S. hypocrisy,<ref name="odom_terrorismtactic">{{cite web|url=http://www.middlebury.edu/media/view/214721/original/OdomPaper.pdf |title=American Hegemony: How to Use It, How to Lose It by Gen. William Odom |format=PDF |accessdate=2014-02-27}}</ref><ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2009/06/03/opinion/03iht-edalbright.html?_r=1 Obama's Muslim Speech], [[The New York Times]], by [[Madeleine Albright]], retrieved on April 25, 2016 "According to Muslim speakers at such events, one fact stands out: When the cold war ended, America needed an enemy to replace Communism and chose Islam...Mr. Obama's dilemma is that no speech, however eloquent, can disentangle U.S.-Muslim relations from the treacherous terrain of current events in places such as Iraq, Afghanistan, Pakistan, Iran and the Middle East...Muslims desire respect and respect demands frankness. We cannot pretend that American soldiers and aircraft are not attacking Muslims."</ref> media-induced hysteria,<ref>{{cite book|last=Lustick|first=Ian S. |title=Trapped in the War on Terror|publisher=University of Pennsylvania Press|isbn=978-0-8122-3983-6|year=2006|origyear=1 September 2006}}</ref> and that differences in foreign and security policy have [[Criticism of United States foreign policy|damaged America's reputation internationally]].<ref name="PEW-2007">{{cite web|url=http://www.pewglobal.org/2007/03/14/americas-image-in-the-world-findings-from-the-pew-global-attitudes-project/|title=America's Image in the World: Findings from the Pew Global Attitudes Project |date=14 March 2007 |publisher=Pew Research Center|accessdate=13 February 2012}}</ref>

==Other Wars on Terror==

In the 2010s, [[China]] has also been engaged in its own War on Terror, predominantly a domestic campaign in response to violent actions by [[Uyghur people|Uighur]] separatist movements in the [[Xinjiang conflict]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cfr.org/china/chinas-war-terror-september-11-uighur-separatism/p4765|title=China's 'War on Terror': September 11 and Uighur Separatism|date=|website=Council on Foreign Relations|accessdate=10 September 2015}}</ref> This campaign was widely criticized in international media due to the perception that it unfairly targets and [[persecutes]] [[Chinese Muslims]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/chinas-war-on-terror-becomes-all-out-attack-on-islam-in-xinjiang/2014/09/19/5c5840a4-1aa7-4bb6-bc63-69f6bfba07e9_story.html|title=China's war on terror becomes all-out attack on Islam in Xinjiang|author=Simon Denyer|date=19 September 2014|website=Washington Post|accessdate=10 September 2015}}</ref> potentially resulting in a negative backlash from [[China]]'s predominantly [[Muslim]] [[Uyghur people|Uighur]] population.

[[Russia]] has also been engaged on its own, also largely internally focused, counter-terrorism campaign often termed a war on terror, during the [[Second Chechen War]], the [[Insurgency in the North Caucasus]], and the [[Russian military intervention in the Syrian Civil War]].<ref>{{cite news| url=http://content.time.com/time/world/article/0,8599,2093529,00.html | work=Time | title=Breaking News, Analysis, Politics, Blogs, News Photos, Video, Tech Reviews - TIME.com | date=19 September 2011}}</ref> Like [[China]]'s war on terror, [[Russia]]'s has also been focused on [[separatist]] and [[Islamist]] movements that use [[political violence]] to achieve their ends.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.gwu.edu/~ieresgwu/assets/docs/demokratizatsiya%20archive/10-4_Cohen.PDF | title=Russia, Islam, and the War on Terrorism | first=Ariel | last=Cohen | accessdate=29 November 2015 }}</ref>

